    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_538200730" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/538200730" />
    <a title="TJ Rowser" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13256753-tj-rowser"><img alt="TJ Rowser" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1348961216p2/13256753.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/538200730?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="TJ Rowser" class="user" itemprop="url" name="TJ Rowser" href="/user/show/13256753-tj-rowser">TJ Rowser</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer538200730" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9646185186432849861">This was a short, mildly entertaining read (at least for me, but I read extremely quickly).<br/>Quick plot summary: ex-soldier meet pretty school teach they fall in love and he goes off to take a private security job in a dangerous country so they can have more money. Their love affair is completely covered in the first few chapters of the book, their relationship is already established and you&apos;ve been told all about it. Enter the person he&apos;s been hired to protect, another woman who&apos;s attracted to ou</span>
  <span id="freeText9646185186432849861" style="display:none">This was a short, mildly entertaining read (at least for me, but I read extremely quickly).<br />Quick plot summary: ex-soldier meet pretty school teach they fall in love and he goes off to take a private security job in a dangerous country so they can have more money. Their love affair is completely covered in the first few chapters of the book, their relationship is already established and you've been told all about it. Enter the person he's been hired to protect, another woman who's attracted to our earnest hero for a bit of tension, that falls a bit flat. And actually that's my biggest problem with the book...<br /><br />The author tells you everything, every detail from exactly how tall someone is, to exactly what day it was, to where the city is located from a larger, more major hub. This is fine, if it's important to the story, but this was done for every detail, and it usually wasn't needed. This was just extra information that didn't really add anything to the story. It's also done in a very matter of a fact manner, which isn't necessarily a bad thing, but I would have liked to have heard more of the author's real voice coming out. I'd also have liked to have had a bit more showing than just telling. Sometimes the discovery is half the fun when you're reading.<br /><br />I do feel the need to mention the paragraph problem. I see this a lot, but usually in the opposite direction. Instead of having lots of short paragraphs (you know what I'm talking about, the one sentence paragraphs that happen four or five times a page), the author has plenty of long ones. When I say long, I mean one went on for two and a half of my kindle pages and it could have easily been broken into smaller chunks. Also spotted a few (only a few, and only one sentence, which seemed to be missing a word, actually interrupted my reading) grammar mistakes, but I'm forgiving of those. It's a self-published book and self-editing can be difficult. Overall it's well put together and well formatted.<br /><br />This is the first book he's written as far as I know, and it's not bad. There's enough glimpses of his voice coming out that I'm interested in seeing what the second book (already available) is like.<br />Overall, for a first effort this a decent little read (even if it was quick for me).</span>
  <a data-text-id="9646185186432849861" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

