<div id="review_607761299" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/607761299" />
    <a title="Julia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11139775-julia"><img alt="Julia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1342837825p2/11139775.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/607761299?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julia" href="/user/show/11139775-julia">Julia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Nook 2940011438400" href="/book/show/14742059-sands-of-betrayal">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11139775-julia?shelf=written-reviews">written-reviews</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer607761299" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7946280434634087861">I&apos;m not really happy that I actually bought this book, though honestly, since it&apos;s by a self-published author, I&apos;m not sure I could have borrowed it from the library.<br/><br/>I&apos;m really not looking forward to writing this review, because I think that self-published authors are awesome and fearless and getting it done the best way that they can. 3 of my favorite authors are self-published and I love their work... and I was really looking forward to reading this book because of the reviews people have put </span>
  <span id="freeText7946280434634087861" style="display:none">I'm not really happy that I actually bought this book, though honestly, since it's by a self-published author, I'm not sure I could have borrowed it from the library.<br /><br />I'm really not looking forward to writing this review, because I think that self-published authors are awesome and fearless and getting it done the best way that they can. 3 of my favorite authors are self-published and I love their work... and I was really looking forward to reading this book because of the reviews people have put out there about the book and the fact that it was one of my favorite book genres, smut. It was also the number one book listed on the recent Goodreads Listopia "Indie Authors Everybody Should Read." So I had high hopes.<br /><br />Like several other reviewers, I am generally suspicious of male romance writers (I feel like they don't quite "get" female fantasies). I am also aware I make myself look hypocritical, since one of my favorite indie authors is male (who coincidentally writes awesome smut). It seems, at least in my case, that the male point-of-view didn't work for me this time. It was extremely obvious that this book was written by a man. The descriptions of the people, both men and women, were obviously written as seen through the eyes of a man. The response Katie writes to Scott's personal ad is obviously written by a man and not a woman. The sex scenes were very obviously written by a man (and I know how men write sex scenes; my husband is in the military and has written me many a letter detailing what he wants to do to me when he gets home). Honestly... I think I've grown up when it comes to the smut I enjoy, because this was way too Harlequin for me. I really did not think it was that hot. And I must be spoiled in real life because Scott did not last long in bed at all. I was far from being as impressed as Katie was.<br /><br />I find foreign accents as attractive as the next American woman, but I found the written Scottish brogue really distracting. All I could hear in my head was Craig Ferguson when Scott was speaking. Not very sexy. I had to laugh out loud in real life when Britney was very obviously pursuing Scott and he was blissfully ignorant, because my husband is the exact same way (except when he realizes a girl is flirting with him, he becomes a total asshole). The "Sands of Betrayal" in the title is still confusing me, even after finishing the book. No one betrayed anyone. Yes, Britney relentlessly pursues Scott and tries to bed him, but she tries and can't and he won't, and she even puts on a nice facade and cooperates with Katie when things go awry. So the title makes no earthly sense at all. The jealousy Katie expresses is very "male" in it's presentation; it reads like how a guy wants think their significant other feels about other women. Me? I would have totally laughed if my husband told me this Britney person was trying to get him into bed. I would have called her myself and told her, "Good luck with that! Have fun. You'll probably die trying." That may just be my ego talking right there, though.<br /><br />The biggest issue I had, however, was how the story was told. The author did a lot of "telling" and not much "showing." It was as if he had written his story directly from his own personal journal, with details that not many people care about (seriously, flight times do not matter in a romance novel). I didn't see the picture painted for me, it was told in excruciating painful minute details. And the frequent use of, "they both enjoyed," "they were both relieved," etc., etc., got old really fast.<br /><br />It's very sweet that this is based on a real-life story (I'm guessing the author and his wife), and however much I really wanted to like this story and wanted it to turn me on... it just didn't do it for me. Obviously, I won't be continuing the series. Good luck to the author, because self-published authors are all sorts of awesome.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7946280434634087861" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


